  "topic_name": "Complementary Angles and Trigonometric Identities",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Complementary angles are two angles that sum to 90 degrees. For complementary angles, sin(θ) = cos(90° - θ) and tan(θ) = cot(90° - θ). The fundamental trigonometric identities include: (1) sin²θ + cos²θ = 1, (2) 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ, and (3) 1 + cot²θ = csc²θ. These identities are essential for simplifying trigonometric expressions and solving equations.",
    "rules": [
      "For complementary angles: sin(θ) = cos(90° - θ), cos(θ) = sin(90° - θ)",
      "For complementary angles: tan(θ) = cot(90° - θ), cot(θ) = tan(90° - θ)",
      "For complementary angles: sec(θ) = csc(90° - θ), csc(θ) = sec(90° - θ)",
      "Fundamental identity: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1 for all angles θ",
      "Dividing the fundamental identity by cos²θ gives: 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ",
      "Dividing the fundamental identity by sin²θ gives: 1 + cot²θ = csc²θ"
    ]
  },
